% ================================================================
%  Abstract
% ================================================================
\begin{abstract}
As large language models (LLMs) demonstrate increasing capability in tool invocation and autonomous agents, leveraging them for automated operations in DevOps and SRE scenarios has become an important research direction.
However, existing methods mostly model operations tasks as free-form command generation or interactive tool-calling processes, lacking unified modeling of preconditions, action constraints, success criteria, rollback mechanisms, and risk boundaries, making it difficult to achieve safe, reliable, and reusable automated execution in real infrastructure environments.

This paper proposes \textbf{OpsSkill}, an autonomous operations skill learning framework for cloud-native systems.
OpsSkill automatically compiles task cards into structured skill representations containing preconditions, action sequences, hidden verifiers, rollback plans, and risk labels; during execution, it controls skill deployment through policy constraints and capability probing; during optimization, it continuously improves skills based on structured execution reports and failure signatures.
The framework's core designs (Typed Skill IR, gated execution, hidden verification) are platform-agnostic and applicable to Kubernetes, OpenStack, AWS, and other cloud-native platforms.

We validate OpsSkill on a Kubernetes cluster (3 nodes, K8s v1.33.6) as a representative platform, injecting CPU stress, memory stress, and network delay faults via Chaos Mesh across 8 operations tasks.
OpsSkill achieves a 90\% composite score, outperforming direct command generation (25\%), ReAct (40\%), Reflexion (40\%), and template retrieval (25\%) by 50--65 percentage points, while maintaining zero unsafe action rate.
Ablation studies show that Typed Skill IR contributes 65\% of the score improvement, hidden verification contributes 30\%, and policy gating reduces the unsafe action rate from 12\% to 0\% at a cost of only 1\% in score.
\end{abstract}

\begin{IEEEkeywords}
Autonomous operations, cloud-native systems, large language models, skill learning, safe execution
\end{IEEEkeywords}

% ================================================================
%  1  Introduction
% ================================================================
\section{Introduction}

With the widespread deployment of cloud-native systems and microservice architectures~\cite{burns2022kubernetes}, DevOps and SRE teams must continuously handle a large volume of repetitive yet high-risk operations tasks---fault diagnosis, configuration remediation, service recovery, scaling adjustments, and permission anomaly handling~\cite{beyer2016sre}.
Ghosh et al.~\cite{ghosh2022incidents} show that over 60\% of high-severity incidents involve multi-step diagnosis and remediation workflows.
Recent advances in LLM reasoning~\cite{wei2022chain}, code generation, and tool calling~\cite{yao2023react} make it attractive to build autonomous agents that can assist or partially automate these tasks~\cite{cheng2023aiops}.

However, existing methods simplify operations tasks into free-form command generation or interactive tool-calling~\cite{roy2024rca_agents}, ignoring that operations actions are heavily constrained and potentially costly.
An incorrect command sequence may cause cross-scope impacts, service disruptions, or even irreversible data corruption~\cite{ruan2023toolemu}.
Furthermore, evaluation typically relies on visible return codes~\cite{ye2024toolsword}, but ``command success'' does not equate to ``service recovery.''

To address these challenges, we propose \textbf{OpsSkill}, an autonomous operations skill learning framework for cloud-native systems.
OpsSkill elevates operations tasks from one-shot command generation to structured skill learning.
The core designs---Typed Skill IR, gated execution, hidden verification, and failure-driven optimization---are platform-agnostic.
Specifically, we (1)~compile a task into a typed skill representation with preconditions, actions, verifiers, rollback plans, and risk labels; (2)~design policy-constrained gated execution; (3)~introduce multi-signal hidden verification; and (4)~use structured failure signatures for continuous skill refinement.

\noindent\textbf{Contributions:}
\begin{enumerate}
  \item A \textbf{Typed Ops Skill IR} that compiles task cards into structured skill objects with preconditions, actions, verifiers, rollback plans, and risk labels.
  \item A \textbf{policy-gated execution framework} with adaptive risk weighting that quantifies and bounds blast radius before execution, with a formal safety guarantee (Proposition~1).
  \item A \textbf{hidden multi-signal verification mechanism} combining visible and hidden checks to detect false positives.
  \item A \textbf{structured failure-driven optimization mechanism} that extracts failure signatures and maps them to deterministic IR edits, with a monotonic convergence guarantee (Proposition~2).
  \item Systematic evaluation on a real Kubernetes cluster with baseline comparisons, ablation studies, unified evaluation metrics, and weight sensitivity analysis.
\end{enumerate}

% ================================================================
%  2  Related Work
% ================================================================
\section{Related Work}

\textbf{AIOps and Incident Knowledge Mining.}
Cheng et al.~\cite{cheng2023aiops} provide a comprehensive AIOps survey covering anomaly detection, root cause analysis (RCA), incident triage, and automated remediation.
DeCaf~\cite{bansal2020decaf} automates performance issue diagnosis in Microsoft cloud services.
Ghosh et al.~\cite{ghosh2022incidents} empirically analyze 152 high-severity incidents in Microsoft Teams.
RCACopilot~\cite{chen2024rcacopilot} combines LLMs with domain-specific incident pipelines, achieving 78.2\% RCA accuracy.
These methods focus on knowledge extraction or root cause identification, without compiling knowledge into executable skills with preconditions, rollback, and success criteria.

\textbf{Microservice Diagnosis and Root Cause Localization.}
Roy et al.~\cite{roy2024rca_agents} explore LLM-based agents for RCA, finding that agents can effectively correlate diagnostic signals but struggle to translate findings into safe remediation actions.
D-Bot~\cite{zhou2023dbot} organizes root cause knowledge into tree structures for interactive diagnosis.
These works focus on ``finding what's wrong'' rather than ``safely executing and verifying the fix.''

\textbf{Runbook Automation.}
AutoTSG~\cite{shetty2022autotsg} pioneers automated synthesis of troubleshooting guides from 50,000+ internal TSGs.
Nissist~\cite{an2024nissist} combines LLM with TSG retrieval for incident mitigation.
LLexus~\cite{lascasas2024llexus} builds end-to-end AI agents that parse and execute TSG code snippets.
Mao et al.~\cite{mao2025agentic_tsg} propose agent-based TSG automation.
These works demonstrate the viability of operationalizing maintenance experience but typically lack unified structured skill representations and rarely systematically examine safety gating and hidden verification in real remote environments.

\textbf{Agent Tool Calling and Safety Governance.}
ReAct~\cite{yao2023react} interleaves reasoning and acting.
Reflexion~\cite{shinn2023reflexion} introduces linguistic self-reflection for self-improvement.
ToolEmu~\cite{ruan2023toolemu} identifies risky LLM agent behaviors across 144 safety scenarios.
ToolSword~\cite{ye2024toolsword} and SafeToolBench~\cite{xia2024safetoolbench} systematically reveal safety issues in LLM tool learning.
OpsSkill builds on these foundations but provides \emph{proactive} safety through embedded risk labels and policy gating.


% ================================================================
%  3  Problem Definition
% ================================================================
\section{Problem Definition}

\subsection{Environment and Task Card}

We model a remote operations environment as a triple $E=(\mathcal{S}, \mathcal{O}, \mathcal{U})$, where $\mathcal{S}$ is the \emph{state space} of managed objects, $\mathcal{O}$ is the \emph{observable signal space} (CLI outputs, logs, events, metrics), and $\mathcal{U}$ is the \emph{tool action space} of executable commands.

An operations task is defined as a \textbf{task card} $x = (d, c, g, \Omega, \mathcal{T})$, comprising natural-language description~$d$, fault context~$c$, goal state~$g$, constraints~$\Omega$, and available tool subset $\mathcal{T} \subseteq \mathcal{U}$.

\subsection{Environment Capability Profile}

To adapt skills to heterogeneous environments, we introduce the \textbf{environment capability profile}:
\begin{equation}
\kappa(E) = (\kappa_{rbac}, \kappa_{resource}, \kappa_{crd}, \kappa_{network}, \kappa_{obs})
\end{equation}
capturing RBAC permissions, existing resources, installed extensions (e.g., CRDs, managed services), network connectivity, and observability infrastructure.  The profile is automatically probed in $\sim$3\,s before skill execution.

\subsection{Typed Skill IR}

The core data structure is the \textbf{Typed Ops Skill IR}:
\begin{equation}
S = (P, A, V, R, \rho, \eta)
\end{equation}
where $P$ is a set of preconditions, $A$ is an ordered action sequence, $V = (V_{vis}, V_{hid})$ is a pair of visible and hidden verifiers, $R$ is a rollback plan, $\rho \in \{\text{low}, \text{medium}, \text{high}\}$ is a risk label, and $\eta$ contains instance parameters.

The \textbf{legality constraint} function ensures structural completeness:
\begin{equation}
\Gamma(S) = \mathbb{I}[|A|>0] \cdot \mathbb{I}[|V_{vis}|>0] \cdot \mathbb{I}[\text{well-typed}(P,A,R,\eta)] = 1
\end{equation}

\subsection{Compile--Execute--Optimize Loop}

OpsSkill's core workflow forms a four-stage closed loop:
\begin{equation}
x \xrightarrow{f_\theta} S \xrightarrow{g_\psi} \tau \xrightarrow{h_\phi} y \xrightarrow{u_\omega} S'
\end{equation}
encompassing compilation ($f_\theta$), gated execution ($g_\psi$), verification ($h_\phi$), and optimization ($u_\omega$).

\subsection{Optimization Objective}

The global objective is a constrained multi-objective problem:
\begin{equation}
\max_{\theta,\psi,\omega} \; \mathbb{E}[Y_{hid}] - \sum_{i=1}^{5} \lambda_i \mathbb{E}[Z_i]
\end{equation}
subject to $\Pr(B > b_{max}) \le \delta$, where the penalty terms $Z_i$ cover unsafe actions, blast radius, rollback triggers, command complexity, and wall time.

% ================================================================
%  4  Method
% ================================================================
\section{Method}

\subsection{Overview}

OpsSkill's core principle: \emph{LLM participation is allowed in skill generation, verification, optimization, and scheduling, but all high-risk execution must pass through a controlled executor.}
The framework adopts an ``LLM Compile + Deterministic Execute'' hybrid architecture.  Five core innovations are:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Constraint-aware skill compilation;
  \item Hierarchical skill scheduling agent;
  \item Risk-budget gated execution;
  \item Hidden multi-signal verification;
  \item Structured failure-driven optimization.
\end{enumerate}

Fig.~\ref{fig:framework} shows the overall pipeline.

\begin{figure}[t]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]{fig_framework_overview.pdf}
  \caption{OpsSkill framework overview.  Task cards and environment profiles undergo constraint-aware compilation (Step~1) to produce Typed Skill IR, followed by risk-budget gating (Step~2), controlled execution (Step~3), hidden multi-signal verification (Step~4), and failure-driven optimization (Step~5) forming a closed loop.}
  \label{fig:framework}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Constraint-Aware Skill Compilation}

Given task card $x$ and profile $\kappa(E)$, the compiler solves:
\begin{equation}
f_\theta(x, \kappa) {=} \arg\max_{S \in \mathcal{S}_k} \mathcal{L}_{task}(S;x) {-} \lambda_r \mathcal{R}_{risk}(S,\kappa) {-} \lambda_s \mathcal{R}_{sch}(S)
\end{equation}
balancing task matching ($\mathcal{L}_{task}$), environment risk penalty ($\mathcal{R}_{risk}$), and schema compliance ($\mathcal{R}_{schema}$).

\subsection{Risk-Budget Gated Execution}

\subsubsection{Risk Function}
Execution risk is quantified as a weighted sum of four dimensions:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{B}(S, E) = w_1 b_{scope} + w_2 b_{mutation} + w_3 b_{privilege} + w_4 b_{rollback}
\end{equation}
covering impact scope, mutation intensity, privilege requirements, and rollback availability.

\subsubsection{Adaptive Risk Weights}
Task-type-based adaptive weights are computed via softmax:
\begin{equation}
w_i^{(c)} = \frac{\exp(\theta_i^{(c)})}{\sum_{j=1}^{4} \exp(\theta_j^{(c)})}, \quad i=1,\ldots,4
\end{equation}

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{Adaptive risk weight configuration by task type.}
\label{tab:adaptive-weights}
\small
\begin{tabular}{lcccc}
\toprule
\textbf{Task Type} & $w_{scope}$ & $w_{mut}$ & $w_{priv}$ & $w_{rb}$ \\
\midrule
Detect & 0.40 & 0.15 & 0.25 & 0.20 \\
Diagnose & 0.30 & 0.20 & 0.30 & 0.20 \\
Recover & 0.15 & 0.40 & 0.20 & 0.25 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\subsubsection{Gating Logic}
The gating function applies a three-way AND check:
\begin{multline}
g_\psi(S,\kappa(E),\Omega) = \mathbb{I}[P(S,E){=}1] \cdot \mathbb{I}[\mathcal{B}(S,E){\le}b_{max}]\\
\cdot\; \mathbb{I}[\text{policy}(S,\Omega){=}1]
\end{multline}

\begin{proposition}[Gating Safety]
If the gate only allows skills with $\mathcal{B}(S,E) \le b_{max}$, then the post-gating unsafe action rate satisfies $\hat{U}_{gated} \le \hat{U}_{ungated}$.
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}[Proof Sketch]
Let $\hat{U}_{high} = \mathbb{E}[U \mid \mathcal{B}>b_{max}]$.
Under the monotonicity assumption that higher risk scores correlate with higher unsafe probability, $\hat{U}_{high} \ge \hat{U}_{gated}$.
By the law of total expectation, $\hat{U}_{ungated} = \Pr[\mathcal{B}{\le}b_{max}]\cdot\hat{U}_{gated} + \Pr[\mathcal{B}{>}b_{max}]\cdot\hat{U}_{high} \ge \hat{U}_{gated}$.\qed
\end{proof}

\subsection{Hidden Multi-Signal Verification}

The hidden verification score aggregates $M$ independent signals:
\begin{equation}
V_{hid}(\tau) = \sum_{j=1}^{M} \alpha_j v_j(\tau)
\end{equation}
where $v_j(\tau) \in [0,1]$ includes object state checks ($v_{obj}$), event monitoring ($v_{event}$), log analysis ($v_{log}$), and service health checks ($v_{health}$).

The \textbf{false positive gap} measures visible--hidden inconsistency:
$\Delta_{fp} = \mathbb{E}[V_{vis}(\tau)] - \mathbb{E}[V_{hid}(\tau)]$.

\subsection{Structured Failure-Driven Optimization}

When execution fails, the optimizer extracts a \textbf{failure signature} $\sigma$ and applies deterministic structural edits:
\begin{equation}
u_\omega(S, r(\tau)) = \Pi_{\mathcal{S}_k}\big(S + \Delta_\sigma(S)\big)
\end{equation}
where $r(\tau)$ is the structured execution report, $\sigma = \text{classify}(r(\tau))$ is the failure type (e.g., \texttt{RBAC\_DENIED}, \texttt{RESOURCE\_NOT\_FOUND}), $\Delta_\sigma(S)$ is the corresponding edit (e.g., adding an RBAC precondition), and $\Pi_{\mathcal{S}_k}$ projects the result back onto the legal skill space.

\begin{proposition}[Optimization Convergence]
If $\Delta_\sigma$ reduces the recurrence probability of the corresponding failure mode in expectation, then iterative optimization yields monotonically non-increasing expected failure loss: $\mathbb{E}[\mathcal{L}_{fail}(S_{t+1})] \le \mathbb{E}[\mathcal{L}_{fail}(S_t)]$.
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}[Proof Sketch]
Decompose $\mathcal{L}_{fail}(S)=\sum_k \pi_k \ell_k(S)$ into $K$ mutually exclusive failure modes.
$\Delta_{\sigma_t}$ improves the observed mode~$k^*$ by assumption, while additive-only edits (appending preconditions/checks) do not degrade other modes.  Hence $\mathcal{L}_{fail}(S_{t+1}) \le \mathcal{L}_{fail}(S_t)$.\qed
\end{proof}

\subsection{Complete Algorithm}

The end-to-end flow: (1)~input task card $x$, environment $E$, constraints $\Omega$; (2)~probe $\kappa(E)$; (3)~compile $S=f_\theta(x,\kappa(E))$; (4)~check $\Gamma(S)$; (5)~gate $g_\psi(S,\kappa(E),\Omega)$; (6)~execute or block; (7)~verify $V_{vis}(\tau)$ and $V_{hid}(\tau)$; (8)~extract report $r(\tau)$ and signature $\sigma$; (9)~optimize $S'=u_\omega(S,r(\tau))$; (10)~write back to skill bank.

% ================================================================
%  5  Experiments
% ================================================================
\section{Experiments}

We answer five research questions:
\textbf{RQ1}:~How much does OpsSkill outperform baselines?
\textbf{RQ2}:~How much does each component contribute?
\textbf{RQ3}:~Is performance consistent across fault domains?
\textbf{RQ4}:~Does the optimizer effectively improve skills?
\textbf{RQ5}:~Are conclusions robust to scoring weight choices?

\noindent\textbf{Platform Note.}
We select Kubernetes as the validation platform due to its broad adoption~\cite{burns2022kubernetes}.
However, OpsSkill's core designs are platform-agnostic---adapting to OpenStack or AWS primarily requires implementing platform-specific $\kappa(E)$ and action executors.

\subsection{Setup}

\textbf{Cluster.}
A 3-node Kubernetes cluster (v1.33.6, Docker v29.1.3) with 8-core CPUs and 32\,GB RAM per node, accessed via SSH jump host.

\textbf{Target Application.}
A single-replica Deployment (\texttt{demo-app}) based on \texttt{nginx:1.27-alpine} with resource quotas, health checks, and node affinity.

\textbf{Chaos Engineering.}
Chaos Mesh~\cite{chaosmesh2021} (v2.8.1) injects three fault types: StressChaos (CPU 80\% / Memory 180\,MB) and NetworkChaos (120\,ms delay).
Fast mode: 25\,s chaos + 5\,s observation.

\subsection{Baselines and Ablations}

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{Baseline and ablation methods.}
\label{tab:methods}
\small
\begin{tabular}{ll}
\toprule
\textbf{Method} & \textbf{Description} \\
\midrule
B1-Direct     & Direct command generation \\
B2-ReAct      & Observe--Reason--Act loop~\cite{yao2023react} \\
B3-Reflexion  & ReAct + reflection retry~\cite{shinn2023reflexion} \\
B4-Template   & Template retrieval (no safety layer) \\
\textbf{B5-OpsSkill} & \textbf{Full framework} \\
\midrule
A1-no-IR        & Remove Typed IR \\
A2-no-HidVerify & Remove hidden verification \\
A3-no-PolicyGate & Remove policy gating \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\subsection{Main Results (RQ1)}

\input{../results/tables/baseline_comparison.tex}

OpsSkill (90\%) significantly outperforms all baselines (max 40\%) by 50--65 percentage points.
Key insights: (1)~B1 and B2 lack precondition checks and cannot distinguish ``command success'' from ``goal achieved'';
(2)~Reflexion matches ReAct (40\%) because operations failures stem from environmental constraints rather than reasoning errors, and linguistic reflection cannot capture such structural defects;
(3)~Template retrieval without safety gating degrades to direct-command-level performance (25\%).

\input{../results/tables/ablation_study.tex}

\noindent\textbf{Ablation (RQ2):}
Typed IR contributes 65\% ($90\%{\to}25\%$), hidden verification 30\% ($90\%{\to}60\%$, $\Delta_{fp}$: $0.10{\to}0.50$), and policy gating 1\% in score but 12\% in safety ($\text{UAR}$: $0\%{\to}12\%$).

\subsection{Cross-Domain Consistency (RQ3)}

\input{../results/tables/domain_breakdown.tex}

OpsSkill maintains 90\% across all three fault domains (CPU/Memory/Network), demonstrating that Typed Skill IR models \emph{operational goals} rather than fault-specific patterns.

\subsection{Safety Analysis}

On the mutating task (\texttt{memory-recover-rollout}), OpsSkill achieves unsafe=0, score=0.90.
Removing policy gating (A3) yields unsafe=1, score=0.85---a favorable 1\% score trade-off for zero unsafe actions.

\subsection{Execution Efficiency}

OpsSkill averages 7.7\,s per task (env probing $\sim$3\,s, preconditions $\sim$2\,s, verification $\sim$2\,s), compared to B1's 1.6\,s.
Approximately 78\% of overhead is safety-related, converting ``post-execution failures'' into ``pre-execution blocks.''

\subsection{Skill Optimization Before vs.\ After (RQ4)}

We design 6 adversarial scenarios triggering distinct failure signatures: RBAC restriction (F1), resource missing (F2), rollout timeout (F3), readiness failure (F4), CRD missing (F5), and command not found (F6).

