% ================================================================
%  6  Discussion
% ================================================================
\section{Discussion}

\textbf{Why Structured IR Outperforms Free-Text Reasoning.}
The 50-point gap between OpsSkill and ReAct arises because Typed Skill IR encodes operations knowledge as constrainable, verifiable structures.
Free-text reasoning cannot be formally verified ($P_{ratio}=0,\;V_{vis}=0$).
OpsSkill compiles the same knowledge into a $(P,A,V,R)$ tuple, enabling formal checking at every stage.
This aligns with AutoTSG~\cite{shetty2022autotsg} and D-Bot~\cite{zhou2023dbot} in structuring maintenance knowledge, but extends to safety-constrained execution.

\textbf{Safety--Efficiency Trade-off.}
Removing policy gating loses only 1\% score but raises UAR from 0\% to 12\%.
In production, one unsafe mutation can cause minute-level service disruptions.
This is consistent with findings by ToolEmu~\cite{ruan2023toolemu} that even the strongest agents produce risky behaviors in $\sim$23.9\% of test scenarios.

\textbf{Structured vs.\ Linguistic Optimization.}
$\Delta_\sigma$ produces deterministic, idempotent edits on specific IR fields, while Reflexion's free-text reflection lacks structural anchors.
The dominant optimization pattern (4/6 scenarios) is converting runtime failures into compile-time blocks via precondition augmentation.

\textbf{Evaluation Fairness.}
Under the unified metric, OpsSkill's advantage \emph{increases} because baselines score zero on precondition and verification dimensions.
Weight sensitivity analysis (5 configurations) confirms robustness.

\subsection{Limitations}

(1)~\emph{Scale}: 3-node cluster with 8 tasks and 3 fault domains; larger-scale cascading faults untested.
(2)~\emph{Scoring}: Fixed weights may not suit all task types.
(3)~\emph{LLM dependency}: Skill compilation uses DeepSeek-V3; verification uses heuristic rules only.
(4)~\emph{Determinism}: Human-authored skill IRs yield zero variance; LLM-generated IRs may introduce variability.

\subsection{Threats to Validity}

\emph{Internal}: The scoring function may favor structured methods; mitigated by hidden verification as a method-agnostic evaluation layer (55\% of total score is cluster-state-based).
\emph{External}: Kubernetes-only validation; mitigated by platform-agnostic IR design.
\emph{Construct}: Researcher-designed task cards rather than production incidents; mitigated by grounding in real SRE experience~\cite{beyer2016sre}.

% ================================================================
%  7  Conclusion
% ================================================================
\section{Conclusion}

We presented OpsSkill, an autonomous operations skill learning framework for cloud-native systems.
Through the ``LLM Compile + Deterministic Execute'' design philosophy, OpsSkill combines LLM knowledge compilation with formal safety guarantees.

In 64 experiment trials (8 methods $\times$ 8 tasks) on a Kubernetes cluster:
OpsSkill achieves 90\% composite score (50--65 pp above baselines), zero unsafe action rate, consistent cross-domain performance (std $<$3\%), and 18\% average optimization improvement.
Ablation shows Typed IR contributes most ($-$65\%), followed by hidden verification ($-$30\%) and policy gating ($-$1\% score, $+$12\% UAR).
Both propositions and sensitivity analyses support the robustness of these conclusions.

Future work includes LLM end-to-end skill compilation, large-scale validation, cross-platform generalization (OpenStack, AWS), and closed-loop self-optimization.

